1 Historical Background
The immense progress in scientic research has led to some Nobel prize-winning exper-
iments being found in the curriculum of an undergraduate lab. This point is evident from
a list of just a few such experiments: the Zeeman eect, e/m of electrons, the Frank-Hertz
experiment, the Bragg spectrometer, the oil drop, and the h/e experiments of Millikan, the
study of the Richardson equation, the cloud chamber, the study of nuclear resonance and
others. The Compton eect is also a member of this family and is a landmark in modern
physics.
Arthur Holly Compton was working with X-rays and was studying their scattering at
dierent angles and by dierent materials. A Bragg crystal spectrometer was used to
analyze the wavelength present in the scattered radiation and it was found that part of the
scattered radiation was shifted to longer wavelengths (relative to the incident wavelengths)
in a manner that was independent of the atomic number of the scattering material and
which depend only on the angle through which he was able to derive the relation between
the scattered wavelength and the incident wavelength 0
0= (h/m0c)(1 cos )=0.024(1 cos )
A(1)
as well as other relations for the energy of the scattered electron, etc... [1]
Comptons groundbreaking work laid the foundation for the understanding of photon-
electron interactions, supporting the wave-particle duality of light. This discovery, known
as the Compton Eect, provided crucial evidence for the quantum nature of electromagnetic
radiation. The experimental validation of this phenomenon earned Arthur Holly Compton
the Nobel Prize in Physics in 1927. The Compton wavelength, associated with the change
in wavelength during scattering, remains a fundamental constant in quantum mechanics.
This experimental prowess continues to be a pivotal component of modern physics educa-
tion, emphasizing the enduring impact of Nobel Prize-winning experiments in shaping the
undergraduate curriculum.

4 Results and Discussion
4.1 Rest-Mass of Electron
Thus the rest mass of the electron calculated from the linear t in the gure: 10 is
5029.6 keV. The actual value of the electron rest mass is 511 keV, which falls well
under the error range of the calculated value from the experiment.
4.2 Further observation
The rest mass calculated from Region II is very close to the electrons rest mass (511
keV). So, the prominently shifted peaks in Region II are due to the scattering from electrons.
The incident energy of the -ray photons should be around 662 keV, but from the gure:
10, we get the energy to be around 602 keV. So, we encounter ambiguity.
To resolve this, we try to analyze the peak shifting in Region I and nd out if the 662
keV peak is submerged into some other scattered photon peak due to the nucleus of the
atom.

5 Error Analysis
5.1 Error in Experimental Data
The experimental setup for the angle-dependent measurement is very crude. A sig-
nicant amount of error is associated with it. Most of this is systematic error and
can be reduced to a great extent with proper setup. An error of 5in the angle
measurement is always the case in such a crude setup.
The number of channels to detect limits the gamma detector. However, we are taking
a xed number of impulses. The probability distribution of the impulses over the
range of energies should not vary much.
The steel rod we used may be thick, leading to the absorption of some low-energy
peaks, which we expect to see. This can also be why the intensity of peaks in Region
II is very low.
The shape of the radiation is not a single point, and we could not put it inside a lead
block. Thus, we did not get a point source which is desired.
5.2 Methods of Reducing the error
Using a rotatory base can help in proper alignment during angle-dependent measure-
ments.
Using a thinner steel rod may help us accurately resolve the secondary peaks (Region
II).
Making a proper setup by which we can approximate the source to a point source
will signicantly reduce the error and better the spectrum resolution.
12
Taking the data for a long duration or taking a large number of impulse counts can
improve the resolution of the spectrum.
6 Conclusions
The Compton scattering at various angles and the Compton wavelength of electrons
are measured. The result obtained roughly agrees with the values of the existing literature.
Still, some changes in the experiment can lead to proper measurements and, thus, good
results. The angle-dependent shift in the spectrum and the wavelength-dependent shift
shows the signicance of treating both electron and light to be particles.

8 Appendix
8.1 High Energy Photon Interaction with materials
[2]
Compton scattering is one of the four main processes that happens when a high-energy
photon interacts with a material. Those processes are:
Photo-eect: an electron absorbs a photon, which then interacts with the crystal.
(E < 500keV )
13
Compton scattering: a photon scatters o an atomic electron, the electron re-
coils, and gains kinetic energy, the original photon changes direction and loses energy
corresponding to the recoil energy of the electron.(500keV < E < 5MeV ).
Pair production: a photon (with energy > 1.2MeV ) converts into an electron
positron (anti-electron) pair. The electron is stopped in the crystal, and the positron
eventually annihilates with an atomic electron and produces two 0.511 MeV photons
that may or may not be detected.
Rayleigh scattering: a photon scatters o an atom without excitation.
